column11: American firms added 3 million new staff to their payrolls in the past year, and the expectation is that the American labour market will continue to expand (The World in 2016). The Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) releases two preliminary estimates of total monthly non-farm payroll employment prior to releasing the final estimate (BLS employment). The question will be suspended on 31 January 2016 and will be closed when the BLS releases its final estimate for January on 1 April 2016.

column6: Economists polled by MarketWatch predict the number of new jobs created in January 2016 will fall below 200,000 after a large 292,000 gain in December.

Building on Okun's Law, I have run a regression with monthly GDP growth and put in an estimation for January 2016 GDP growth. I have looked at the relationship between December and January in terms of job growth for the past ten years and the past 5 years. I have compared job growth in January to average job growth throughout the previous year, and each suggest that job growth in January 2016 will be between 212,000 jobs and 256,000 jobs. More techniques suggest above 250,000 jobs, so I gave it a higher probability.

In period Jan 11 - Sep 15 of 57 months, 21 months below 175, 24 months between 175-225, and 12 months over 225. However, I will put 50% weight on the 2015 figure and underweight 2011 at 8%, so in 2015, 2 months below 175, 8 months between 175-225, and 2 months over 225. A lot of the indicators introduced here imply long-term implications, such as GDP, weather, negative China spillover. I think we should also consider short-term or real-time indicators like the stock market and the USD. A current strong USD is overall positive for US since it is a net importer and it attracts foreign investment into the country. However, during the first week of Jan, roughly 112 billion USD have exited the stock market and the S&P 500 index almost tumbled by 5%, partly due to the overbought trend in the prior 2 months. The downtrend in the stock market persisted throughout the second week of Jan. Job growth is a lagging indicator so I put more weight on the weak data in Dec over recent ones in Jan. Initial jobless claims increased by 10K to 293K last week, and manufacturing conditions in the Northeast contracted slightly this month, according to the Philadelphia Federal Reserve Bank.** Furthermore, the Fed "report's reading on future expectations...continued to decline and is now at the lowest levels since November 2012"***. These variables have only modestly powerful predictive value (as far as I can tell), but in the absence of data that have the opposite predictive valence, I'm tempted to be a wee bit more bearish about the January jobs report.

Screwed up the numbers with my last prediction. The average job growth over the last 6 months has been 228k. If we assume the growth is normally distributed around the mean (It isn't, but nonetheless), we get a standard deviation of about 63. This gives a 48% chance of it being below 225k, with a 20% chance of being below 175.

Based on a crappy statistical analysis I did, which found mean job growth over the last 6 months to be 269.5k. Falsely assuming the data are normally distributed, I estimated a standard deviation of ~65k, which makes getting less than 175k about 6% while the 175-225 range is about 19%.

- Using employment data (http://www.bls.gov/eag/eag.us.htm) I calculated how often the January employment growth in the last three years fitted within the three groups of <175k, 175-225k, and >225k. This gave a probability of 50%, 20% and 30% respectively - The next step I took was to look at how employment growth % in January followed the previous quarter (average of Oct, Nov and Dec) in the previous 10 years. Then, using the 2015 Q4 employment data, I used the % growth for each year to calculate how many more jobs would have been created in January. This provides a probability of 60%, 10%, and 30% for each group - Given that this data includes a number of months where growth was negative, I then analyse the likelihood of negative growth occurring in January, as the recessionary years have a large impact on the overall probability - Initial jobless claims rose in the week ended Jan 9 by 7,000 (http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-14/initial-jobless-claims-in-u-s-unexpectedly-increased-last-week) - The increase in interest rates may cause a slowdown in employment, but I would expect the results of this to lag a number of months as the effects on investment and recruitment feed through (I also expect the result to be mild) - Employment is also at it's highest in the last 10 years, and given the slow level of growth in the economy, some doubt whether further growth in jobs is sustainable given the rapid job growth in 2015 - The likelihood of a recession in January is low, given that we are already two-thirds of the way through the month. Assuming that the economy returns to a recession on average once every 6 years, this gives a probability of 17% that a recession will occur in any given year. Citi (http://uk.businessinsider.com/r-watch-for-us-recession-zero-interest-rates-in-china-next-year-citi-says-2015-12?r=US&IR=T) predict a probability of 65% of a recession in 2016, although my expectation is that this is punchy given the fed's optimism about the economy. I would still expect the probability in 2016 to be greater than 17%, so lets meet in the middle at 41%. By pro-rating -

I know a number of you enjoy statistical modeling, and I enjoy viewing your work. I'm wondering if anyone has considered modeling this employment estimate against change in GDP or consumer spending, or whatever. Some of you have mentioned that "employment is a lagging indicator." I don't know if your preferred metric is readily available through 4Q2015, but estimates might be available. It would be some work, digging out all that historical metric and employment data. So the exercise would have a two-fold purpose: to validate the claim that employment is a lagging indicator (of whatever metric you select), and to develop a forecast which I might follow!

Based on measurement of past BLS estimates, it seems that the Bureau ended up overestimating on its predictions by between 10% and 20% at this time last year (projections for Jan/Feb 2015: https://web.archive.org/web/20150309030044/http://data.bls.gov/timeseries/CES0000000001?output_view=net_1mth; versus actual numbers for Jan/Feb 2015: http://data.bls.gov/timeseries/CES0000000001?output_view=net_1mth). However, in the prior year, it seems to have underestimated by almost 50%, projecting a growth of 113,000 jobs but getting 166,000 instead. With this fairly wild variation in mind and the current trends seen in past Januarys, it seems that the most likely outcomes will be in between 175,000 and 225,000, but potentially on the higher end of that range, even bleeding into 225,000+.

- It’s hard to see much of a connection between job growth in December of one year and job growth in the following January over the last 10 years. - 6 times the December numbers have been better, and 4 times they’ve been lower. But the average ((median + mean/2) over the same period of the absolute value of the difference between December and January is 26. That looks like it’s a good predicator, but the standard deviation is over 140! - In fact there seems to be a a slightly looser connection between job growth in November of one year and job growth in the following January over the last 10 years. The average ((median + mean/2) over the same period of the absolute value of the difference between December and January is 33. Here the standard deviation is also pretty big, though smaller than that for December: 124. - So I think that the December numbers predict about a modest (2%) increase in likelihood.
